Education CS George Magoha has appointed Mike Kuria to serve as the chief executive of the Commission for University Education. According to a statement by CUE Chair Chacha Nyaigotti, Kuria will replace the current CEO Mwenda Ntarangwi whose term ends on September 4. The professor will serve for a five-year term, which is renewable once. Kuria formerly served as the director of the center for quality assurance at Daystar University. “Kuria is a multi-skilled and versatile leader with extensive experience and expertise in quality assurance in higher education and beyond,” the statement reads. Kuria will be expected to regulate, oversee university education in the country and contribute to university education initiatives. According to a notice by CUE, 15 candidates were shortlisted from a list of 49 who submitted their applications. Laban Peter Ayiro was shortlisted alongside Emily Achieng, Dismus Bulinda, Elizabeth Wangari, Everlyne Kisembe, Mike Kuria and Geoffrey Muluvi. Others are Benedict Mwavu, Francis Gichuki, Grace Njoroge, Nathan Oyori, Maurice Oduor, Gilbert Opanga, Douglas Shitanda and Jackson Too. Ntarangwi was appointed CEO on September 6, 2017, for a five-year term. Ntarangwi took over from David Kimutai Some, who had served at the top position since 2012.